Are these considered different overloads in C++?

```cpp
void foo(double) { }
void foo(const double) { }
```

explanation:
These are the same declaration for overloading purposes, so the second declaration is a redefinition error.
Example:
void f(int);
void f(const int); // same as f(int), not a new overload

// But reference/pointer qualifiers do matter:
void g(int&);
void g(const int&); // different overloads

A function signature identifies a callable declaration for overload resolution. In practice, it is based on function name and parameter type list, with member-function qualifiers (like `const`, ref-qualifiers) also relevant.
Example:
void f(int);
void f(double);   // different signature

struct S {
  void g();
  void g() const; // different signature from non-const member
}

